Data Exploration using R

Summary

The goal is to learn some approaches to understand and visualize continuous and categorical variables from the Iris Data Set.

Methods

These are the individual methods for measuring the central value:

  • Mean
  • Median
  • Mode (most common value among a group)

These are the individual methods for measuring the variance or dispersion of the data:

  • Standard Deviation
  • Range
  • Quartiles
  • Inter Quartile Range (IQR)
  • Coefficient of Variation

These statistical methods can be used to compare variables:

  • Correlation Coefficient
  • Linear Models
  • Anova
  • Pearsons chi-squared test

Analysis

R libraries

We need a couple of libraries for the exercises. Lets load them all upfront:

library(ggplot2)
library(reshape2)
library(Hmisc)
library(pastecs)

Calculating the mean and sd

Lets load the data set and calculate the mean and sd of the sepal length feature.

data(iris)
print(dim(iris))
## [1] 150   5
print(head(iris))
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 2          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2  setosa
## 4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2  setosa
## 5          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4  setosa
mean(iris$Sepal.Length)
## [1] 5.843333
sd(iris$Sepal.Length)
## [1] 0.8280661

Calculating quantiles

We can also calculate the 25%, 50%, and 75% quantile of the data.

quantile(iris$Sepal.Length, probs=c(0.25, 0.5, 0.75))
## 25% 50% 75% 
## 5.1 5.8 6.4
median(iris$Sepal.Length)
## [1] 5.8

Lets visualize these quantiles in a histogram of sepal length.

ggplot(data=iris, aes(x=Sepal.Length)) + geom_histogram(bins=30) + geom_vline(xintercept=c(5.1, 5.8, 6.4))

Lets do the same with a boxplot.

ggplot(data=iris, aes(x="Sepal.Length", y=Sepal.Length)) + geom_boxplot()

ggplot(data=iris, aes(x="Sepal.Length", y=Sepal.Length)) + geom_boxplot() + geom_hline(yintercept=c(5.1, 5.8, 6.4), color="lightblue")

With the help of ggplot2 we can visualize all features based on the outcome variable Species.

lf = melt(iris, id=c("Species"))
ggplot(data=lf, aes(x=Species, y=value)) + geom_boxplot(aes(group=Species)) + facet_wrap(~variable, scales="free_y")

ggplot(data=lf, aes(x=value)) + geom_freqpoly(aes(group=Species, color=Species), stat="bin", bins=30) + facet_wrap(~variable, scales="free")

Comparing two variables (features)

Scatter plots are useful to investigate the relationship between two variables.

ggplot(data=iris, aes(x=Sepal.Length, y=Petal.Length)) + geom_point()

You can stratify the scatter plot by the Species variable using facet_wrap.

ggplot(data=iris, aes(x=Sepal.Length, y=Petal.Length)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~Species)

Lets fit a linear model to get the linear relationship between sepal length and petal length.

lm(Petal.Length ~ Sepal.Length, data=iris)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Petal.Length ~ Sepal.Length, data = iris)
## 
## Coefficients:
##  (Intercept)  Sepal.Length  
##       -7.101         1.858
ggplot(data=iris, aes(x=Sepal.Length, y=Petal.Length)) + geom_point() + geom_abline(slope=1.858, intercept=-7.101)

ggplot(data=iris, aes(x=Sepal.Length, y=Petal.Length)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm")

We can check the correlation between sepal length and petal length.

cor(iris$Sepal.Length, iris$Petal.Length)
## [1] 0.8717538
cor.test(iris$Sepal.Length, iris$Petal.Length)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  iris$Sepal.Length and iris$Petal.Length
## t = 21.646, df = 148, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.8270363 0.9055080
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.8717538

To compare a categorical variable with a continuous variable we can use a boxplot.

ggplot(data=iris, aes(x=Species, y=Sepal.Length)) + geom_boxplot()

We can use Anova to find out whether all species have the same mean or if at least one species has a different mean for sepal length.

av=aov(Sepal.Length ~ Species, data=iris)
print(summary(av))
##              Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)    
## Species       2  63.21  31.606   119.3 <2e-16 ***
## Residuals   147  38.96   0.265                   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Finally, we may want to compare two categorical variables. Lets create an artificial categorical variable Petal.Width.Bin with 4 levels.

iris$Petal.Width.Bin = cut(iris$Petal.Width, breaks=4, labels=c("tiny", "small", "large", "xlarge"))
iris$Petal.Width.Bin = factor(iris$Petal.Width.Bin)
ggplot(data=iris, aes(x="Petal.Width", y=Petal.Width)) + geom_point(aes(color=Petal.Width.Bin))

ggplot(data=iris, aes(x=Species, y=Petal.Width.Bin)) + geom_jitter(aes(color=Petal.Width.Bin), width=0.2, height=0.2)

We can then use Pearsons chi-squared test to find out if all the differences between the categories arose by chance.

chisq.test(x=iris$Species, y=iris$Petal.Width.Bin)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  iris$Species and iris$Petal.Width.Bin
## X-squared = 235.53, df = 6, p-value < 2.2e-16

Questions

A couple of questions for yourself to explore the data further.

  • What is the inter quartile range (IQR) of petal width?
  • What is the median petal width?
  • What is the correlation coefficient of sepal width and petal width?
  • Generate a scatter plot of petal width and sepal width.
  • Stratify the scatter plot of petal width and sepal width by Species.
  • Challenge: What is the correlation coefficient of sepal width and petal width for each Species separately?
